Deceased","1346":"1346","1500":"1500","about 1405":"about 1405","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1405":"1405","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walrond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): of Normin origin, a variant of   Waldron  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Worland","meanings":["English (Cambridge): of Norman origin, possibly a metathesised variant of   Walrond   (see   Waldron  )."]},{"name":"Waldron","meanings":["English and Irish (Mayo): from the Norman personal name <i>Waleran</i>, <i>Galeran</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Walahram</i>, Old French <i>Galeran(t)</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner’ + <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’. Compare   Walraven  . In Ireland, where it is common, this name was Gaelicized early as <b>Mac Bhalronta</b>, also later as <b>Mac Bhaildrin</b> and <b>de Bhaldraithe</b>.","English: habitational name from a place in Sussex named Waldron. The placename derives from Old English <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’ + <i>ærn</i> ‘building’.","History: This is the name of a prominent NH family, established there since the 17th century. Richard Walderne (born <i>c.</i> 1615) came to New England from Alchester, Warwickshire, England, <i>c.</i> 1640 and settled at Dover, NH."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Walrond was born in 1384, in Bradfield, Essex, England, his father, John II Walrond, was 39 and his mother, Mrs. John II Walrond, was 31. He married Julianna Mellor. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1430, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1384–1430":"1384–1430","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1346":"1346","1500":"1500","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1405":"1405","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1384–1430":"1384–1430","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1346":"1346","1500":"1500","about 1405":"noin 1405","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1405":"1405","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1384–1430":"1384–1430","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1354–Female":"1354–Décédée","1346":"1346","1500":"1500","about 1405":"environ 1405","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1405":"1405","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, Angleterre","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, Angleterre","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Walrond est né en 1384, à Bradfield, Essex, Angleterre, son p